// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Adventure hooks
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: adventure_hook
A merchant offers {2d6 * 50} gold to escort a mysterious locked chest across {region_name} — he refuses to say what is inside.
A child in the village of [@village_name] claims to have seen the dead walking in the old graveyard at midnight.
The local lord has vanished; his last known location was {location}.
Three adventurers set out for {location} a week ago — only their weapons have returned, dragged by a frightened mule.
A bounty of {1d4 * 100} gold is posted for the capture — alive — of a fugitive wizard last seen near {location}.
An ancient map surfaces at auction, apparently showing a vault beneath {location} filled with pre-empire treasure.
The river that supplies [@village_name] has run black for three days; something upstream is wrong.
A dying courier delivers a sealed letter intended for someone who died years ago — and the contents reference something that cannot yet have happened.
Strange lights have been seen above {location} every night for a month; farmers refuse to work their fields.
A beloved temple healer has gone missing; her notes mention a secret ritual she planned to perform alone at {location}.
The party wakes in an unfamiliar location with no memory of the last {1d6 + 1} hours — and one of them is missing.
A sealed crypt beneath [@village_name] has opened from the inside for the first time in two centuries.
A tax collector sent to {region_name} never returned; the second one who went to look for the first also vanished.
Something has been stealing children from [@village_name] every new moon — and the next one is in three days.
A war that ended {1d6 + 10} years ago may not be entirely over; old soldiers are being found dead with fresh wounds.
A scholar auctions a cursed tome found in {location} — the bidding war descends into murderous chaos before the sale closes.
A fire in [{village_name}'s archive|the city records office|a monastery scriptorium] destroys what may have been the only copy of a crucial document — or does it?
The party is approached by a dying thief who presses a key into their hands and says only: "{location}. Third door. Don't trust the [|steward|priest|merchant|guard]."
Every mirror in [@village_name] has been showing the same face for three days. No one knows whose face it is.
A knight errant arrives bearing a challenge — not to combat, but to prove a disputed truth before it's used to start a war.

