Table: ally_role
a local [|innkeeper|blacksmith|herbalist|scholar|retired soldier|hedge wizard] who knows more than they let on
a [|young|grizzled|cynical|idealistic] [|guard|scout|mercenary|priest] who needs the party as much as they need them
a [|disillusioned|former|captured and freed] member of the villain's organisation
a [|travelling merchant|wandering scholar|disgraced noble|excommunicated priest] with crucial information
a [|child|elder|last survivor] who witnessed something no one else will believe

Table: ally_personality
Forthright and direct — says exactly what they mean, which occasionally causes problems.
Carefully guarded — reveals information in pieces, never the whole picture at once.
Warm and earnest — genuinely wants to help, which makes their inevitable complication worse.
Sardonic and weary — helps because no one else will, not because they believe it will work.
Anxious and over-prepared — brings too many plans, all of them half-right.
Fiercely loyal once trust is earned — and almost impossible to win over in the first place.
Cheerful in the face of danger — which either means courage or denial; hard to tell which.

Table: ally_secret
They are being blackmailed by the villain and may be forced to betray the party.
They know more about the party's true purpose than they have revealed.
They are related to — or were once close to — the villain.
They have already failed once in a situation almost identical to this one.
They are terminally ill and operating on borrowed time.
They have been lying about their identity; their real background complicates everything.
They are the one who originally set the villain's plan in motion, years ago.

Table: ally_offer
Detailed knowledge of {location} — [|maps|patrol routes|hidden entrances|structural weaknesses].
A contact inside the villain's organisation who may be turned.
A [|magic item|key|pass phrase|seal of safe conduct] that opens a locked door in the plot.
[|Healing|Smithing|Arcane research|Intelligence gathering] support during the mission.
A safe house and supply cache [|outside the city|inside the dungeon|near the villain's lair].

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Location features
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: location_feature
A [|collapsed|flooded|recently disturbed] [|corridor|chamber|stairwell] that suggests someone has been here recently.
A [|shrine|altar|throne|vault door] that is clearly significant — [|recently desecrated|still functional|deliberately hidden].
A [|guard post|patrol route|watch position] that, if neutralised quietly, opens a path the villain doesn't expect.
Prisoners — {1d4 + 1} [|villagers|soldiers|scholars|adventurers] held in a [|cage|cellar|sealed chamber].
A [|library|archive|laboratory|scriptorium] where the villain's plans are partially documented.
Traps: [|pressure plates|tripwires|magical wards|a sealed room filled with gas] protecting the inner sanctum.
Environmental hazard: [|rising water|a crumbling ceiling|spreading fire|unstable arcane residue|a necrotic aura].
A [|secret door|hidden passage|underwater tunnel|collapsed section that can be dug through] known only to those who look carefully.
Evidence of a previous expedition — [|equipment|bones|a journal|a warning scratched into the wall].
A [|summoning circle|ritual site|magical focus|corrupted ley line node] that powers the villain's operation.
A guardian creature [|chained|bound by magic|patrolling on a fixed route|sleeping] that need not be fought.
An NPC in the wrong place: [|a spy|a thief|a lost child|a trapped spirit] who complicates the mission.

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Travel encounters
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: travel_encounter
En route: the party encounters [|a patrol of {1d6 + 2} soldiers bearing the villain's colours|a group of refugees fleeing from {location}|a wandering [|merchant|scholar|hermit] with unexpected information].
A bridge or ford is controlled by [|bandits|a troll|a guardian construct|a customs officer with impossible demands].
The road passes through [|a village in the grip of fear|an abandoned hamlet|a camp of mercenaries for hire|a burned waystation].
A fellow adventuring party crosses paths with the group — [|rivals|allies|one of their old enemies in the lead|the only survivors of the last attempt].
Weather turns: [|a blizzard|a fog so thick visibility drops to 10 ft|torrential rain that floods the road|a heatwave that drains stamina] forces a change of plan.
A creature — [|injured|frightened|magically bound|carrying a message] — blocks the road and refuses to move.
A [|merchant caravan|diplomatic envoy|funerary procession] passes; someone in it recognises [|a party member|a party member's name|the party's destination] and reacts.
The party finds the aftermath of a battle: [|{1d4 + 2} bodies|a single survivor|discarded equipment suggesting something went very wrong].
A distress call — [|fire|screaming|a signal arrow|a horn blast] — from the road ahead; investigating means a delay.
Signs of the villain's activity: [|freshly planted spies in the local village|supply wagons bearing their mark|a noticeboard with wanted posters featuring someone the party knows].

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Complications
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: complication
The party is being [|followed|framed|watched|manipulated|impersonated] by a [|rival adventuring group|shadowy organisation|vengeful NPC|unknown third party|the villain's spy].
An NPC the party trusts is [|working for the villain|keeping a dangerous secret|slowly being corrupted|not who they claim to be|under a magical compulsion].
The villain has [|already struck once|taken a hostage the party cares about|sabotaged their supplies|bribed a key ally|one step ahead — every time].
The location is [|structurally unstable|warded against magic|partially flooded|under enemy surveillance|rigged to collapse].
Time pressure: the ritual / attack / collapse / deadline happens in {1d6} days.
A moral dilemma: the most effective solution would cause serious [|harm to innocents|destruction of something irreplaceable|violation of the law|permanent damage to a faction].
Political interference: a [|lord|guild|church|kingdom|spy network] with its own agenda is trying to control the outcome.
Environmental hazard: [|plague|famine|wildfire|blizzard|flood|earthquake] complicates travel and resources.
The party's goal and the villain's goal are the same — and one of them will have to give way.
A faction that should be helping is instead making demands of its own before it will act.
One party member has a personal stake in the outcome that the others don't yet know about.
The evidence points to the wrong person — following it naively will create a new enemy.
A prisoner taken by the villain has already been [|turned|killed|replaced with a doppelgänger|freed and is running their own plan].
The party's reputation precedes them: [|the locals don't trust them|the villain prepared specifically for their abilities|an old ally became an enemy while they were away].
The most powerful potential ally [|refuses to help unless a personal favour is repaid|is under the villain's thumb|has their own agenda that may betray the party at a critical moment].
A powerful NPC [|dies unexpectedly|is revealed to be the villain|switches sides at the worst moment|holds information that only becomes relevant too late].

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// The twist
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: twist
The villain is not the true threat — they are trying to stop something far worse.
The quest giver has been lying: their real motive is [|personal greed|a family secret|revenge|fear of exposure|a deal with a worse power].
One of the party's trusted allies is revealed to be [|a spy|the villain's relative|under a compulsion|not human|the original villain in disguise].
The "artefact" / "prisoner" / "treasure" the party seeks does not exist — it was bait.
The location itself is [|sentient|cursed to repeat a tragedy|a prison for something that must not be released|slowly dying|actively hostile to the party's goal].
Success will cost the party something precious and irreplaceable.
The villain had a point: the people they were fighting for are [|corrupt|guilty|responsible for the villain's suffering|planning something worse themselves].
The final confrontation reveals a connection between the villain and one party member's past.
There is a second villain who has been manipulating both sides from the start.
Destroying the threat would trigger a catastrophe; the solution requires sacrifice, not violence.
The villain wins — and the scenario is about surviving the aftermath and planning what comes next.
Everything was a test: the real patron, enemy, or challenge is revealed only after the party has committed.
The party has been working for the wrong side. The villain, when confronted, reveals the truth and it holds up.
The location holds something that was never supposed to be found — and now that the party knows it exists, someone will come for them.

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Rewards
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: reward
{1d6 * 100} gold pieces found among the villain's possessions.
\a [|+1|+2|+3] [|sword|axe|bow|shield|staff|dagger|warhammer|rapier|spear|trident] of [|striking|protection|speed|returning|fire|frost|lightning|seeking|warning].
A [|spell scroll|ritual book|map|coded letter|forbidden tome] that opens a new adventure thread.
The gratitude of [@village_name]: they offer free [|lodging|equipment repairs|healing|horses|information] for life.
\a rare [|potion of healing|potion of greater healing|potion of flying|potion of invisibility|elixir of health|oil of etherealness].
A deed to [|a small plot of land|a disused mine|an abandoned building|a share in a merchant vessel|a safehouse in the nearest city].
A favour owed by [|a noble|a guild master|a wizard|a temple elder|a retired general|the city watch captain] — to be called in at a future date.
Knowledge: the villain's documents reveal the location of something [|dangerous|valuable|long-lost|that changes history].
A [|sending stone|ring of feather falling|bag of holding|cloak of elvenkind|boots of the winterlands] found in the villain's personal effects.
A title or minor rank: the party is granted [|a letter of marque|a knight's charter|a warden's commission|a guild seat] — useful and politically complicated.
A contact inside [|a thieves' guild|the royal court|an arcane academy|a temple hierarchy] who owes the party a substantial debt.
{1d4 * 100} gp worth of [|rare spell components|alchemical reagents|exotic trade goods] that will take [|weeks|a month] to liquidate.

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// Side quests
// ----------------------------------------------------------------

Table: side_quest
Locate a missing person — a [@village_name] resident last seen near {location}.
Recover a [|stolen|cursed|lost|hidden] [|family heirloom|holy relic|magical component|piece of armour|spell focus] for a grateful NPC.
Investigate rumours of [|disappearances|undead activity|strange lights|unexplained fires|livestock mutations] near [@village_name].
Deliver a sealed message to a contact in [@village_name] before a [|rival|pursuer|deadline] can intercept it.
Escort a [|wounded soldier|frightened scholar|disillusioned cultist|refugee family|captured witness] to safety.
Clear a [|cave system|ruined building|stretch of road|river crossing|mountain pass] of [|bandits|monsters|undead|traps|mercenaries] blocking passage.
Obtain a [|rare herb|spell component|piece of information|tool|key|identification paper] needed to overcome a challenge in the main quest.
Defuse a conflict between two factions in [@village_name] before it erupts into open violence.
Discover what happened to the [|last party that tried this|previous owner of the dungeon|founder of the order protecting {location}].
Negotiate the release of a prisoner held by [|a rival faction|a local warlord|an overzealous inquisitor] who has information the party needs.
Find and destroy [|a cache of weapons|a poisoned water source|a blackmail archive|a set of forged documents] before it causes irreversible harm.
Protect a witness who saw something they shouldn't have — and is being hunted for it.
